column10:
[h1]It's definitely a hell...[/h1]

[b]If you have experienced "The Forest" and didn't like it, you'll probably hate this one too. In addition to it, be prepared for glitches and bad optimization. Phobic people must be aware: tons of spiders, snakes, insects, rodents, heights (not as much as Tomb Raider, e.g.), deep water, blood, vomit, etcetera. Which make this game, maybe, not suitable for everybody.[/b]

[b](+)[/b] I'll never be in a forest, NEVER, specially Amazon. But I think this game quite catch the feeling of being alone in a truly green hell;
[b](+)[/b] Devs must have had help from some expert survivalist people, and they did quite well, either on graphics or on animations (eating, healing, etc.);
[b](+)[/b] I kinda like this blueprints construction type (ghosts semi-transparent models of buildings), but its constraints sucks.

[b](-)[/b] Far beyond bugs (or glitches, not insects and such), Green Hell is badly optimized. It's even worse playing Spirits of Amazonia, don't know why. Near tribal camps I got 15~25 fps. Reducing quality and tweaking nvidia settings was the way to get 30~40 fps. A bad joke, don't you think?
[b](-)[/b] Jake Higgins: For an Anthropologist Doctor, who has been studying in the Amazon for 3 years, he's pretty dumb. He can't identify the majority of plants and mushrooms, for example. He's unable to craft something unless he finds an item first;
[b](-)[/b] AI and combat system are poor, so to speak;
[b](-)[/b] There's a pencil on the left side of every map, but why cant Jake write something on the map? A marker? Any stupid person can write down on a paper, even with charcoal. The whole navigation system is a mess. You dropped the ball here, devs;
[b](-)[/b] I don't like The Forest and its stupid inventory system. You just copy/paste it here. Not having a rapid access to items like food or healing, let's call it "clunky mechanics": could add to "like the real world" thing, but not to our fun as players/gamers;
[b](-)[/b] You can die (and will die) horribly and fast for virtually any reason. It's laughable, and you can hear them (devs) laughing at you on every death by poison, fever on infection that they never teach you how to properly treat/clean wounds. Jake is also an imbecile, so yeah! Until you get used to it and know things (I mean search for community guides).


You will definitely get a (virtual) survival experience. A very hard one with Green Hell. There's no guidance, there's no markers, no lights, no interactive map, just your endless battery smart watch (thanks to Mia) and all the knowledge you can get from third-party guides.

It's a 7.0/10.
Not suitable for all survivals audience, for sure.
